1
00:01:18,000 --> 00:01:18,840
Lin Yaozu,

2
00:01:18,840 --> 00:01:20,370
give me your dirty clothes.

3
00:01:21,120 --> 00:01:22,360
What are you doing?

4
00:01:23,400 --> 00:01:24,720
To wash them.

5
00:01:24,920 --> 00:01:27,160
Or are you going to wear them until they mold?

6
00:01:27,160 --> 00:01:28,560
Who's going to wash them?

7
00:01:28,840 --> 00:01:30,039
The washing machine.

8
00:01:30,120 --> 00:01:32,320
Or did you expect us to wash them by hand?

9
00:01:32,840 --> 00:01:34,400
But

10
00:01:34,400 --> 00:01:35,400
this is my only set of clothes.

11
00:01:35,400 --> 00:01:37,000
What if they don't dry after washing?

12
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:38,360
We have a dryer.

13
00:01:39,120 --> 00:01:41,120
They'll dry quickly after washing.

14
00:02:00,120 --> 00:02:01,520
Who would believe this?

15
00:02:01,720 --> 00:02:03,520
Picking someone up off the street,

16
00:02:03,520 --> 00:02:05,180
that's unheard of these days.

17
00:02:06,840 --> 00:02:08,770
If he really did time-travel here,

18
00:02:09,000 --> 00:02:10,199
would you believe it?

19
00:02:10,400 --> 00:02:12,080
What if,

20
00:02:12,080 --> 00:02:13,600
what if he's a scammer?

21
00:02:13,920 --> 00:02:16,120
Scammers have all sorts of tricks now.

22
00:02:19,440 --> 00:02:20,680
What's there to scam?

23
00:02:20,680 --> 00:02:22,160
It's just one meal.

24
00:02:22,360 --> 00:02:23,820
We just need to stay alert.

25
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:25,040
Hold on.

26
00:02:25,040 --> 00:02:26,640
This is more than just a meal.

27
00:02:26,840 --> 00:02:27,680
That guy

28
00:02:27,680 --> 00:02:29,740
is taking a shower in there right now.

29
00:02:44,360 --> 00:02:45,160
Yaoyao,

30
00:02:45,960 --> 00:02:50,120
if he really is a time traveler,

31
00:02:50,520 --> 00:02:53,320
does that mean we've discovered a rift in space-time?

32
00:02:53,320 --> 00:02:55,050
A living fossil of time travel.

33
00:02:55,320 --> 00:02:57,160
If it's true,

34
00:02:57,320 --> 00:03:00,000
we'll get massive internet traffic.

35
00:03:04,320 --> 00:03:05,650
What are you looking at?

36
00:03:08,320 --> 00:03:11,000
Nanyang volunteer mechanics. In 1939,

37
00:03:11,000 --> 00:03:14,120
Tan Kah Kee called upon over 3,200 mechanics to return

38
00:03:14,120 --> 00:03:16,720
to transport supplies on the Burma Road.

39
00:03:16,720 --> 00:03:18,240
Hey, wait.

40
00:03:18,520 --> 00:03:19,600
Tan Kah Kee?

41
00:03:19,600 --> 00:03:21,560
The overseas Chinese who sacrificed his family fortune to build schools?

42
00:03:21,560 --> 00:03:24,320
I even took a picture in front of his statue.

43
00:03:24,320 --> 00:03:24,960
Look.

44
00:03:25,960 --> 00:03:26,760
Yes.

45
00:03:27,440 --> 00:03:28,600
During the War of Resistance Against Japanese Aggression,

46
00:03:28,600 --> 00:03:32,860
he was also the chairman of the Nanyang Chinese Relief General Association.

47
00:03:33,000 --> 00:03:35,460
What did the Relief General Association do?

48
00:03:36,240 --> 00:03:37,880
During the war,

49
00:03:37,920 --> 00:03:40,320
patriotic Nanyang Chinese donated money and supplies,

50
00:03:40,320 --> 00:03:42,600
forming this patriotic salvation organization.

51
00:03:42,600 --> 00:03:43,280
Not only that,

52
00:03:43,280 --> 00:03:46,800
he also called upon over 3,200 Nanyang Chinese mechanics

53
00:03:46,800 --> 00:03:50,000
to return and support frontline supply transportation.

54
00:03:50,280 --> 00:03:53,120
Returning for supply transportation.

55
00:03:53,720 --> 00:03:55,280
Could it be

56
00:03:55,360 --> 00:03:57,360
that he really is a Nanyang Chinese?

57
00:03:59,280 --> 00:04:01,880
Over 1,000 of these returning mechanics died,

58
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:03,600
averaging one death per kilometer.

59
00:04:03,600 --> 00:04:06,600
They were later known as the 'Meritorious Sons'.

60
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:10,680
Nanyang Chinese,

61
00:04:11,600 --> 00:04:12,440
Nan Qiao,

62
00:04:13,200 --> 00:04:16,000
isn't that the abbreviation for Nanyang Chinese?

63
00:04:16,480 --> 00:04:18,410
And Nanyang volunteer mechanics.

64
00:04:29,920 --> 00:04:31,160
Test him.

65
00:04:31,160 --> 00:04:33,000
If he really is a Nanyang mechanic,

66
00:04:33,000 --> 00:04:35,060
he must know the history of that time,

67
00:04:35,120 --> 00:04:36,840
because he lived through it.

68
00:04:37,000 --> 00:04:38,600
If he's a scammer,

69
00:04:38,840 --> 00:04:40,970
he definitely won't know the details.

70
00:04:42,240 --> 00:04:43,480
But if he lies,

71
00:04:43,480 --> 00:04:44,640
you wouldn't know.

72
00:04:46,080 --> 00:04:47,880
Psychology says

73
00:04:47,880 --> 00:04:51,640
a liar's eyes and tone will give them away.

74
00:04:51,920 --> 00:04:52,720
Yaoyao,

75
00:04:52,720 --> 00:04:54,080
let's work together later.

76
00:04:54,080 --> 00:04:55,680
Watch his eyes closely.

77
00:04:57,800 --> 00:05:00,000
You're really smart at times like this.

78
00:05:01,640 --> 00:05:03,800
Watching those suspense and detective shows

79
00:05:03,800 --> 00:05:05,280
wasn't for nothing.

80
00:05:06,480 --> 00:05:08,600
Let's look up more information now.

81
00:05:11,880 --> 00:05:12,880
Seriously.

82
00:05:12,880 --> 00:05:14,600
Took so long, did you fall in?

83
00:05:16,080 --> 00:05:17,520
Lin Yaozu, your clothes.

84
00:05:34,280 --> 00:05:35,600
Ladies,

85
00:05:35,600 --> 00:05:37,440
do you know magic?

86
00:05:39,000 --> 00:05:40,640
How did the clothes dry so fast?

87
00:05:40,640 --> 00:05:41,770
And they smell good.

88
00:05:44,480 --> 00:05:46,840
You two don't look like bad people,

89
00:05:47,680 --> 00:05:48,600
but I...

90
00:05:49,320 --> 00:05:50,680
Who exactly are you?

91
00:05:50,680 --> 00:05:52,520
Nanyang overseas Chinese mechanic, Lin Yaozu.

92
00:05:52,520 --> 00:05:53,640
Then let me ask you,

93
00:05:53,640 --> 00:05:54,720
dare you answer?

94
00:05:55,040 --> 00:05:55,880
Ask away.

95
00:06:08,200 --> 00:06:10,800
What are the 24 sharp turns on the Burma Road called?

96
00:06:10,800 --> 00:06:11,440
The Gates of Hell.

97
00:06:11,440 --> 00:06:12,840
Why are they called the Gates of Hell?

98
00:06:12,840 --> 00:06:14,800
A zigzag road carved into the cliff.

99
00:06:14,800 --> 00:06:16,240
Every vehicle must be equipped with anti-skid chains.

100
00:06:16,240 --> 00:06:18,360
What is opposite Eagle Beak Cliff?

101
00:06:18,360 --> 00:06:19,920
Wangjiang Cliff.

102
00:06:19,920 --> 00:06:22,240
They say if a car crashes on the 1st, it reaches the bottom on the 15th.

103
00:06:22,240 --> 00:06:24,400
What is your biggest fear during transport?

104
00:06:24,400 --> 00:06:25,530
The biggest fear...

105
00:06:29,360 --> 00:06:31,820
is the endless bombing by the Japanese army.

106
00:06:32,040 --> 00:06:32,800
Fear of the cold.

107
00:06:32,800 --> 00:06:34,080
Fear of hunger.

108
00:06:34,080 --> 00:06:36,240
Fear of bandits, miasma,

109
00:06:36,240 --> 00:06:38,170
rogue soldiers, and road bullies.

110
00:06:38,200 --> 00:06:40,130
Fear of slippery roads in the rain.

111
00:06:40,520 --> 00:06:41,600
You could say

112
00:06:43,200 --> 00:06:44,330
we fear everything.

113
00:06:44,960 --> 00:06:46,320
Why fear the cold?

114
00:06:48,120 --> 00:06:49,720
I only realized after I came back

115
00:06:49,720 --> 00:06:51,280
that the roads in Yunnan have

116
00:06:51,280 --> 00:06:52,920
four seasons on one mountain,

117
00:06:52,920 --> 00:06:55,120
and different weather every ten miles.

118
00:06:55,159 --> 00:06:56,840
But the biggest fear

119
00:06:56,840 --> 00:06:59,040
is that the supplies won't reach the frontline.

120
00:06:59,040 --> 00:07:01,570
Because this is the only remaining lifeline.

121
00:07:03,160 --> 00:07:04,600
You mean the Burma Road?

122
00:07:05,120 --> 00:07:06,920
Yes, the Burma Road.

123
00:07:07,560 --> 00:07:10,120
The roads and sea routes that could transport supplies to the frontline

124
00:07:10,120 --> 00:07:12,180
were all cut off by the Japanese army.

125
00:07:12,440 --> 00:07:13,320
Now,

126
00:07:13,320 --> 00:07:15,200
this is the only road left.

127
00:07:16,000 --> 00:07:17,160
Really?

128
00:07:17,320 --> 00:07:18,600
Of course it's real.

129
00:07:19,160 --> 00:07:21,160
Weapons and equipment needed for the resistance,

130
00:07:21,160 --> 00:07:23,000
supplies needed to keep things running,

131
00:07:23,000 --> 00:07:25,330
and basic consumables needed in the rear,

132
00:07:25,440 --> 00:07:27,320
all supplies that cannot be produced domestically,

133
00:07:27,320 --> 00:07:30,240
can only be transported to the frontline via this road.

134
00:07:30,240 --> 00:07:31,800
Then when did you come back?

135
00:07:34,800 --> 00:07:36,930
The 28th year of the Republic of China,

136
00:07:44,920 --> 00:07:45,960
February 18th.

137
00:07:47,120 --> 00:07:48,720
I will never forget this day.

138
00:07:51,080 --> 00:07:52,600
It was New Year's Eve.

139
00:07:56,680 --> 00:07:59,480
We had our reunion dinner on the ship back to China.

140
00:08:00,480 --> 00:08:01,880
80 people.

141
00:08:04,120 --> 00:08:05,320
The Eighty Pioneers.

142
00:08:06,680 --> 00:08:08,840
The Eighty Pioneers.

143
00:08:08,840 --> 00:08:12,360
Why does it sound like a suicide squad?

144
00:08:12,360 --> 00:08:13,240
Suicide squad?

145
00:08:16,240 --> 00:08:17,080
Pretty much.

146
00:08:18,040 --> 00:08:19,000
New Year's Eve,

147
00:08:19,440 --> 00:08:21,040
didn't you think about leaving a day later?

148
00:08:21,040 --> 00:08:22,370
Not even a minute later.

149
00:08:23,880 --> 00:08:25,440
Although I grew up in Nanyang,

150
00:08:25,440 --> 00:08:26,760
my roots are in China.

151
00:08:27,440 --> 00:08:29,440
Now the Japanese invaders are killing my compatriots,

152
00:08:29,440 --> 00:08:30,880
seizing my homeland,

153
00:08:30,880 --> 00:08:32,120
and even...

154
00:08:32,120 --> 00:08:34,049
and even trying to wipe out my race.

155
00:08:34,159 --> 00:08:35,559
The situation on the frontline is urgent.

156
00:08:35,559 --> 00:08:37,880
We can't afford to delay for a single minute.

157
00:08:37,880 --> 00:08:39,480
These Japanese invaders...

158
00:08:42,280 --> 00:08:43,809
Why are you asking all this?

159
00:08:44,520 --> 00:08:46,480
After Huitong Bridge was blown up in '42,

160
00:08:46,480 --> 00:08:48,120
did you all return to Nanyang?

161
00:08:48,120 --> 00:08:49,160
What?

162
00:08:49,160 --> 00:08:50,160
'42?

163
00:08:55,080 --> 00:08:57,240
Huitong Bridge was blown up in '42?

164
00:08:58,440 --> 00:08:59,720
Yes.

165
00:08:59,720 --> 00:09:01,160
In 1942,

166
00:09:01,160 --> 00:09:02,240
to prevent the Japanese army from crossing the bridge

167
00:09:02,240 --> 00:09:03,370
and protect Yunnan,

168
00:09:03,480 --> 00:09:04,960
Huitong Bridge was forced to be blown up.

169
00:09:04,960 --> 00:09:06,720
Isn't it 1941 now?

170
00:09:08,640 --> 00:09:10,640
It's 2025 now.

171
00:09:10,640 --> 00:09:12,770
The war of resistance was won long ago.

172
00:09:15,880 --> 00:09:17,540
The war of resistance was won?

173
00:09:17,840 --> 00:09:19,500
The war of resistance was won.

174
00:09:20,520 --> 00:09:22,400
Lin Yaozu.

175
00:09:22,400 --> 00:09:23,680
If I'm not mistaken,

176
00:09:24,560 --> 00:09:26,360
our time and space have crossed.

177
00:09:45,000 --> 00:09:48,000
Recently, electromagnetic anomalies have appeared in many places.

178
00:09:48,000 --> 00:09:50,320
Experts say it may be related to solar storms.
